title: Breathing and yoga via /r/Fitness
body:
Hi guys, so I had a question about one’s ability to breathe during yoga, namely my own. I am not a flexible guy, to say the least. I’ve got a few extra pounds (25ish lbs) that are slowly coming off. I’m also decently tall at 6'2" and broad of shoulder. I recently started doing yoga again after about 4 years, and I’m having trouble getting air during many poses. Any pose that puts any pressure on the stomach seems to cut my lung capacity by at least half. It feels like I am only able to breathe down in to my stomach, and not bring it up in to my chest. I don’t have any problems with breathing at the gym or during any other part of my life, just during yoga. Is this normal? Or a sign of a weak diaphragm?



Submitted November 27, 2018 at 12:05AM by Cilreve
via reddit https://ift.tt/2KziUuD

summary: Is my approach to weight loss correct? via /r/Fitness
title: Is my approach to weight loss correct? via /r/Fitness
body:
Hey, so I’m a 5'8, 18 year old guy and I’ve been overweight most of my life. Recently, I decided that enough is enough and that I need to change and become more healthy/fit. My knowledge going into loosing weight is that 3500 calories makes up a pound. Our body needs an X amount of calories a day. If we add cardio or excersie to our day, our body needs more calories. Based off of this information I decided to limit my calorie intake. So everyday I just eat approx 1500 calories worth of food. So far it’s been about ~3.5 weeks and I lost 10lbs (started at 215lbs). I’m assuming some of this is water weight but I made some sort of progress. I also have access to my universities gym, I try to go 1-2 times a week and workout my muscles. I don’t really like doing cardio so for now I’m avoiding it. I know it would be better to combine a diet and exercise but I don’t enjoy cardio. I’m just wondering if this approach is healthy for my body and if I should continue doing what I’m doing.



Submitted November 27, 2018 at 01:09AM by Usmainian
via reddit https://ift.tt/2Rj21GT
